<br>
Melees are utterly dependent on gear.  The gap between the best equipped melee and a modestly equipped melee is large, and think is a fair reward for having gear dependency built into their class.<br>
<br>
Casters in comparison, are currently relatively independent of gear, and fair more dependent on level and their spell books.  This is a great advantage.  For example, when I was 49ish, I could solo for experience completely naked except for a stack of malachite while I waited for rez.  The gap between the best equipped caster and a modestly is comparatively much less than for melee, but then that is exactly what I would expect.  It would not be fair for casters to enjoy both the benefits of gear independence and dramatic improvement through gear.<br>
<br>
While I do think it is reasonable to ask that caster gear to make more difference than it currently does, the best gear should not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;uberize&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> casters on the same scale it does melee.<br>
<br>
Separately, I do not find the notion of making casters as dependent on gear as melee particularly appealling.  I see no compelling benefit of making such a radical change to such a fundamental element of class design.<br>
<br>
To be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>as</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> dependent on gear as melees means that the spellbook would have to impotent, and indeed that is what <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Krilen</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> stated:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Simply put, casters need to scale with level and items the way melees do.  Weak as hell with no items, powerful with items.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->At that point, you might as well get rid of the spell book altogether, and put <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>all</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> spells as right-click effects on class specific items.  Only then would casters become as dependent on gear as melees.<br>
<br>
I think that is an absurd idea, and that no one seriously proposes that.<br>
<br>
Instead, what is probably being proposed is that spell books be significantly weakened and caster dependence on gear significantly increased, and I do not find this the least bit compelling as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;fix&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  EverQuest</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in any way.<br>
<br>
Consider the impact on the existing player base if it were implemented.  Either the compensating focus effects would be on existing gear, or it would be on new gear that dropped.  If it were not on existing gear but only new gear, existing casters would find that their power dropped dramatically, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>and</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> having to engage in frenzied competition for those spawns that dropped the necessary items.  Since casters are now significantly nerfed, they would less desirable by groups and guilds whose assistance they would require.  The reduction of power would likely mean that casters could not solo for those items.<br>
<br>
Alternately, suppose the focus effects were retroactively added to existing items, scaled appropriately with the difficulty of obtaining that loot, which is what I think the proponents of this idea would say would be best and fairest implementation.  Immediately, all casters would examine their inventory, and likely discover that they are missing an important focus effect.  Many would be crippled by the lack of appropriate focus.  Those with the greatest variety of spell effects, requiring the greatest number of focus items would be hard pressed to wear adequate resist gear.  What are the odds, for example, that a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Velium Blue Diamond Bracer</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would retroactively include an important focus effect?  Casters would be in the position of making much greater tradeoffs in order to wear resist gear.  But as spell casting is the main activity of casters, there would be no choice but to wear these items, otherwise, as intended by the proposal, spells would be weak.<br>
<br>
As an illustrative analogy, it would be as if almost all resist gear for melees were on weapons, and that in order to gain resists, they would have to use a significantly sub-par weapon.<br>
<br>
Even then, assuming that ensuing chaos comes to an end, and every caster has the necessary focus items <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;appropriate&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for their level, what would be the net effect?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  If you're a casual player, you should be less powerful than a powergamer...I play a lot...You play 1 hour a week...And yet...you're just as powerful as me.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The stated purpose of this proposal is that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;casual&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> players would have their power reduced, while <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;uber&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> players would have their power increased, and so far as I can tell, this is also the only <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;benefit&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that is offered.<br>
<br>
A net transfer of power away from casual players in order to benefit dedicated players simply in order to satisfy the sense of fairness of those who would benefit most from that transfer strikes me as self centered.  Worse, it is exactly those <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;dedicated&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> players that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>already</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> consume the most resources from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  EverQuest</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> such as bandwidth and spawns.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, I find that caster dependence on spell books rather than gear a fundamental design decision and a fair distinction between casters and melee.  I see no credible arguments advanced in favor of this dramatic change, and dire negative consequences.  To the extent that dedicated casters need to be further distinguished from casual casters, I see no reason that cannot be accomplished through no drop spells dropped on raids, rather like the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Ancient Spell Line</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> which is already in the game, and will likely be extended.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
