<i>Paladin-Merchant of Kaladim</i></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A> at: 4/4/02 7:16:48 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umaldisdainatheist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maldisdain Atheist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#333333>(4/1/02 9:58:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=175.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dynamic.gamespy.com/~cazic/cazic/ubb/uploads/StaffOfSerpent2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Caster should remain largely independent of gear</span><hr size=1> Honestly, as an issue of general <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> caster</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> balancing, I tend to agree with Krilen that our dependency on gear needs to be increased.<br>
<br>
At present, there are two vital stats for pure casters: intelligence and mana.  Hit points and armor class are a luxury and resists, while important in certain circumstances, are generally not a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> major</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> determining factor in our gear selection.  The only exception to this &quot;two stat&quot; rule seems to be enchanters: we also need to pull high charisma (though the value of charisma is greatly debated).<br>
----------<br>
<br>
Melees have a much wider range of stats to balance.  Aside from the basic character attributes that are vital to melees (HP, AC, STR, STA, AGI and DEX, also INT/WIS for SKs/Ranger), they have to balance damage ratios, varying weaponskills (and weapon advantages/disadvantages including things like ability to bash), procs, etc.  In the high end game, it's not uncommon to see a melee switch weapons 2-3 times over the course of a fight to maximize/minimize his taunt/damage/proc effects.  In addition, they often have to make the same sacrifices that we do for resists, when needed.<br>
<br>
Each point of strength for a melee is a corresponding increase in Attack.  Each point of Dexterity increases their chance at a proc or critical hit.  Each point of AC increases their damage absorbtion, and every three points of Agility increase their damage avoidance.<br>
<br>
Casters... we have Intelligence (increases our mana pool), Mana (increases our mana pool).  Charisma reduces enchanter resists on something (whether it is just charms, or charms and mezes, is up for debate).  Sure, AC, HP and AGI are nice, but (theoretically) we shouldn't be meleed anyway, so these things are *mostly* luxuries that we persue as secondary stats.<br>
----------<br>
<br>
We need more Prime Requisits, like melees, I think.  We need to be able to optomize our equipment to reduce monster resistances to our spells, to increase the melee power of our pets, to scale up or down our taunt, to increase our base damage (or spell durations, in the case of enchanters).<br>
----------<br>
<br>
I suspect it is too difficult to code this in based on statistics, at this point (unfortunately).  It is not too late to put these abilities on items, however.  Simple things like &quot;+10% Skill Modifier: Specialize Conjuration,&quot; for example, would make a world of difference for me (alteration specialist, though mezes are conjuration based).  Items with Channelling bonuses, effects that increase the difficulty of your magic/fire/cold/poison/disease spells to be resisted... or one line of your spells (perhaps the Shock line for mages, for example).  Items that resist the casting times on clickable items... items with procs that go off based on spell-casting rather than melee... all of these are possibilites.<br>
----------<br>
<br>
It bores me to know that there is a set of gear our there that is the &quot;best&quot; gear than an enchanter can have.  Once he gets that gear, he's done.  Melees have to adjust their gear for certain circumstances... have to prepare for situations where they have to slow, or hold aggro over an entire raid, or bash, or whatever.  But once I get items x, y, and z, all I need do is equip those and go about my business, and that's it.<br>
<br>
Where's the creativity in that?  The problem solving?<br>
----------<br>
<br>
If I have to sustain a nerf to get that sort of variety in my play, so be it.  Go ahead and make mezes virtually impossible to land at a 90 cha... fine with me.  Make them extremely reliable at 255 cha.  Make my alteration spells take longer to cast at a 90 dexterity, but make them take a fraction of that time at a 255.  Give me an item that has a chance of procing a caster-equivalent of avatar whenever I cast (+100 dex, sta, agi, int, mana) or that procs a memory blur on my target.  Give mages and item that can proc a bolt when they cast direct damage spells, or proc Burnout 4 when they summon a pet.  Give clerics items that can proc a 150pt self heal when they cast a heal.  <br>
<br>
Give me things that do 1/10th of this, but give me a reason to choose item x over item y that's a little more complicated than &quot;how much mana does it give.&quot;<br>
