<br>
In fact, after the choice of weapon, one haste item, and base AC and HP, buffs and songs currently have far a more profound effect.<br>
<br>
Gear dependency as described by its proponents would represent a far greater burdern on casters than melees.  Not only would casters have to level to get the spells, they would have to obtain the spells themselves, as well as the focus items to improve those spells so that they are no longer <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;weak as hell.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  In contrast, melees would have no equivalent of a spell book or spells to limit them, but only a small number of skills that are trivial to obtain and improve through their use.<br>
<br>
The advocates of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Weak Non-Focused Casters</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, in pursuit of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;fairness&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for themselves, neglect the impact this would have on casual and especially new players.  How many newbie casters, discovering the impotence of their spells, contrary to the tenets of every fantasy role playing game they have ever played, would give up before 20th level?  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Twinking,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> while listed as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;benefit&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of their proposal, only benefits those who can twink, and functions are a barrier to entry for new players.  As it is, the existance of classes that are relatively independent of gear provides an adequate powerbase for new players to learn the mechanics of the game without being so weak that they quit in frustration.<br>
<br>
Casters would also experience more difficulty than melees with gear dependency because trade-offs between various items would be much more involved.  For melees, only a few inventory slots are critical: the weapon hand or hands, and whatever slot their haste item occupies.  All other slots are essentially interchangeable: any slot can used to swap out AC and HPs for resists or whatever.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, under <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Weak Non-Focused Casters</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, caster might be dependent on half a dozen or more inventory slots, several of which might be critical.  That is, the caster might own only one focus item that makes a critical spell, like mezz, charm, haste, or slow non-impotent, and so that item could not be swapped out for other gear.  In order to move power away from spells and onto gear, key spell effect factors like magnitude of effect, duration, mana cost, spell casting speed, opponent resistance, spell range, and so on.  As has been demonstrated with the existing focus items, some focus effects that are appropriate for damage are not appropriate for other effects such as healing, so that damage, healing, and haste/slow percents are unlikely to all be effected by the same magnitude of effect focus item.<br>
<br>
The net result would be that equipment slot trade-offs would be much more onerous for casters than melees, as more items would be absolutely necessary.  In order to make those trade offs easier, those who could afford it would have to acquire substitutes for critical focus items so they could trade them off if necessary.  So a moderately well equipped caster would have to carry three sets of gear: the gear they wear, resist gear, and back up focus items to allow them to wear their resist gear.<br>
<br>
In other words, making casters dependent on gear would, for most casters, make them even more dependent on gear than melee are.<br>
<br>
Presumably <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;dedicated&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> players could obtain the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;best&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> items, with multiple appropriate effects on good slots, but all others would suffer.  In general, the suffering of other casters is ignored by the proponents of this proposal, who are concerned primarily that they have be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;unfairly&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> denied the fruit of their labors, and are willing to take them at the expense of others.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> People who spend more time in the game SHOULD advance further than those who do not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Why can't this be accomplished simply by the introduction of more compelling caster loot, especially at the high end, without weakening spells and making casters dependent on gear?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I personally feel that casters should experience the same upgrades that melees experience from getting better items.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As the game is presently designed, that would be unfair to melees.  Since casters are largely independent of gear, and melees are dependent, it is only fair that the gap between the best and worst equipped casters be less than than the best and worst equipped melees.  Casters enjoy the benefit of gear independence, they should not therefore improve as much through the best equipment as melees do.<br>
<br>
I am not against improvements in caster gear, especially in the end game.  I agree that current caster loots by and large are not compelling, and do not function as an adequate reward.  However, when adding new caster loots to the game, while they may improve casters more than current loots does, along the lines of the focus effects, they should not be as potent as melee gear.<br>
<br>
What the proponents of this idea are saying is that no reasonable new or retrofit caster loots bearing new and existing focus effects could possibly be a sufficient reward for their effort, and that instead existing caster must be made weaker.  Worse, the cost of caster gear dependency would be paid by those least likely to benefit from it, while the proponents are all players who would gain it the most.<br>
